Alighiero Boetti

Alighiero Boetti, the Italian conceptual artist, continues to be a bright s=
pot in the Contemporary art market. Nine works with an estimated presale va=
lue of nearly $2 million are on offer this week in London. Total auction sa=
les for Boetti peaked in 2022, when almost $31 million worth of his art was=
 sold, 80 percent of which came from works priced above $1 million.

Since then, Boetti=E2=80=99s auction totals have dropped, but only because =
of the lack of high-value sales. More Boetti lots were sold in 2023 than in=
 2022. So far this year, as many Boetti works were sold as in all of 2022.

For an artist who made works out of humble materials and commissioned artis=
ans to fabricate his conceptual works, it should be fitting that his market=
 fills out throughout lower price points. In 2023, and so far in 2024, less=
 than half of the
auction value has come for works sold for seven figures.

Sotheby=E2=80=99s sold an embroidered work for $914,400. On Thursday, Chris=
tie=E2=80=99s will sell the remainder of a large collection of works consig=
ned by a single owner across sales in New York and London, including an emb=
roidered 25 x 25 cell grid of letters with a =C2=A3350,000 estimate and a t=
hird-party guarantee. The guarantee isn=E2=80=99t surprising considering on=
e of these 1988 25 x 25 works, also from the same collection but composed o=
f a series of 25 smaller 5 x 5 cell panels, sold for nearly $900,000 in Mar=
ch.

Antony Gormley

Irish sculptor Antony Gormley has had better years on the art market than 2=
023=E2=80=94namely 2017, when a maquette for his monumental Angel of the No=
rth sculpture sold for nearly $7 million in London. But his sales have been=
 remarkably consistent over the past six years, falling from more than $8 m=
illion in 2018 to a low of $6.2 million in both 2020 and 2021, before risin=
g again to more than $8 million last year. (It=E2=80=99s artists like Gorml=
ey, with consistent demand, that provide us with a baseline measure of the =
art market.) Gormley has three sculptures in Christie=E2=80=99s sale, all e=
xamples of his human forms, ranging in estimates from =C2=A360,000 to =C2=
=A3300,000.

Scott Kahn

Since his first auction sale in late 2021, Scott Kahn=E2=80=99s art has bee=
n heavily trafficked on the market. During 2022 and 2023, more than 30 work=
s were auctioned for a total of $10.2 million (2022) and $8 million (2023).=
 But since then, sales activity has pretty much come to a halt, with only o=
ne painting reaching the auction block so far this year. It was also announ=
ced that David Zwirner=E2=80=99s gallery would be taking over global repres=
entation of the artist.

The one work that sold this year, also at Christie=E2=80=99s, handily excee=
ded its estimate to make nearly $250,000. That suggests there is still subs=
tantial demand for Kahn=E2=80=99s work around the world; Zwirner=E2=80=99s =
reach as a gallery should be able to capitalize on that demand. With those =
facts in mind, I'll be watching the sales of two paintings from the early 1=
990s at
Christie=E2=80=99s on Thursday. Both are estimated at a level similar to th=
e work sold earlier in the year.

When Zwirner took over representation of Katherine Bernhardt in 2021, sales=
 volume rose and her top prices increased substantially. Kahn=E2=80=99s auc=
tion record was set early in this market run, but he=E2=80=99s had high-val=
ue confirmation sales as late as November of 2023.

William Copley

In the late 1940s, while living in Los Angeles, William Copley became frien=
dly with a group of Surrealist expatriates, including Man Ray and Max Ernst=
=2E He sold their work in his Beverly H=
ills gallery funded by his adoptive fa=
ther, the owner of a chain of newspapers. Married five times in the course =
of his 77 years, Copley abandoned his first wife and two children in Los An=
geles in the early 1950s to move to Paris and paint. Although he died more =
than a quarter-century ago, his estate was only recently moved to Kasmin Ga=
llery.

That representation, combined with a surge in interest in Surrealism among =
young artists=E2=80=94not to mention a show of Copley=E2=80=99s work at the=
 Fondazione Prada in 2017=E2=80=94provoked new auction demand for Copley=E2=
=80=99s art. In 2021 and 2022, Copley=E2=80=99s sales volume reached a new
high, with the most lots ever auctioned in 2022. This year, Copley=E2=80=99=
s average price has reached a new high of more than $125,000. A 1973 work, =
La Grand Bouffe, is on offer at Phillips ( https://www.phillips.com/detail/=
william-n-copley/UK010424/51?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2=
