16px; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><i>But first=E2=
=80=A6</i><br/><br/><ul style=3D"margin:0;color:#000000;font-size:16px;line=
-height:30px;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;list-style-type:square;mso-specia=
l-format:bullet"><li><i>Boston=E2=80=99s Museum of Fine Arts is looking for=
 a new director</i>: The turnover in museum leadership continues. Early thi=
s year, the Frick announced that director <b>Ian Wardropper </b>would retir=
e in 2025 after a 14-year tenure. Late last week, <b>Matthew</b> <b>Teitelb=
aum</b>, the director of Boston=E2=80=99s Museum of Fine Arts, announced th=
at he would also retire in 2025 after a decade in charge. <br/><br/>Teitelb=
aum, a scholar of Canadian art, had been the director of the Art Gallery of=
 Ontario for 17 years=E2=80=94where he led the $306 million expansion and r=
enovation of the museum by <b>Frank Gehry</b>=E2=80=94before joining the M.=
F.A. In Boston, there would be no grand building
project; instead, Teitelbaum=E2=80=99s tenure was focused on creating stron=
ger ties to the community, renovating conservation facilities and galleries=
, and building a strategic 10-year plan. The museum will only be halfway th=
rough that plan when Teitelbaum retires. <br/><br/>Although Teitelbaum over=
saw the acquisition of important collections of Dutch art, Chinese art, and=
 photography at M.F.A., his tenure will be remembered most for fostering a =
stronger connection between the museum and the public. At a recent conferen=
ce, MoMA=E2=80=99s <b>Glenn</b> <b>Lowry</b> underscored the importance of =
these programming and community initiatives when he expressed his fear that=
 a populist Congress, having intimidated and facilitated the firing of univ=
ersity presidents, would next turn toward museums. He advocated for strong =
community ties through vibrant programming while acknowledging the challeng=
es to funding these programs. Donors, after all, prefer to underwrite build=
ings and art, not
internships for curators.</li><br/><li><i>Seattle Art Museum names new dire=
ctor and C.E.O.</i>: The Seattle Art Museum announced today that it has cho=
sen the C.E.O. of Tulsa=E2=80=99s Philbrook Art Museum, <b>Scott</b> <b>Stu=
len</b>, as its new director and chief executive. As with Teitelbaum in Bos=
ton, Stulen=E2=80=99s emphasis will be on engagement. S.A.M. praised Stulen=
 for having a =E2=80=9Ctransformative approach to museum practice, a deep c=
ommitment to inclusivity, and a focus on art as a means to increase civic e=
ngagement.=E2=80=9D During his eight years in Tulsa, Stulen presided over =
=E2=80=9Can exponential growth=E2=80=9D in attendance. Before leading the P=
hilbrook, Stulen was the curator of audience experiences and performance at=
 the Indianapolis Museum of Art. </li><br/><li><i>Gagosian hires Mike Ovitz=
=E2=80=99s curator</i>: For the past 17 years, <b>Viet-Nu Nguyen</b>, who g=
oes by Nu, was the curator of the Ovitz Family Collection. She has just joi=
ned Gagosian as a director in Los Angeles, where she will
work with artists including <b>Mark</b> <b>Grotjahn</b> and <b>Jonas</b> <b=
>Wood</b>. Gagosian seems to be shoring up his relationships with the artis=
ts who supply his selling machine. </li><br/><li><i>Christie=E2=80=99s to s=
ell some cool stuff that Paul Allen owned</i>: Christie=E2=80=99s announced=
 today that they would continue their relationship with <b>Paul G. Allen</b=
>=E2=80=99s estate by holding two online auctions and one live sale in earl=
y September. The works on offer range from a Gemini spacesuit (estimated at=
 $80,000) to a signed letter from <b>Albert</b> <b>Einstein</b> to <b>F.D.R=
=2E </b>foreshadowing the possibility o=
f an atomic bomb (estimated at $4 mill=
ion) to a DEC PDP-10 computer (estimated at $30,000), similar to the machin=
e that Allen and <b>Bill</b> <b>Gates</b> used to create Microsoft=E2=80=99=
s <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt=
2UktxclJLZ0dRVWJ3czMwTlFjYWtPRUJWczZCZz0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcG=
VkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvQWx0YWlyX0JBU0lDP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1XYWxsK1Bvd2VyKy0rU1VCU=
0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4NiUyRjI1JTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY29udGVudD1XYWxsK1Bvd2VyKy0r=
U1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4NiUyRjE2JTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGl=
vblx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW9cdTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhND=
JhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjkzOTk1M=
30/f7b85660965f28994d7def15073178b7ecc3e0f2634c83e769d89b7a69e14116" style=
=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">firs=
t software product</a></u> in 1975. The online sales will close on Septembe=
r 12; the live sale will take place on September 10. (Just a reminder: We s=
till haven=E2=80=99t seen some important works from Allen=E2=80=99s art col=
lection. Presumably, his sister and heir <b>Jody</b> <b>Allen</b> is holdin=
g on to them.)</li><br/><li><i>Sotheby=E2=80=99s announces new Paris headqu=
arters</i>: I=E2=80=99ve reported this before, but just to put a bow on it:=
 Yesterday, Sotheby=E2=80=99s officially announced that it would be moving =
its Paris headquarters down the Rue du Faubourg Saint-Honor=C3=A9, to the f=
ormer home of Galerie Bernheim-Jeune, in October. The full building gives S=
otheby=E2=80=99s a 200-seat auction room on the ground floor, visible from =
the street, and exhibition spaces that open into the auction room. There is=
 also a =E2=80=9Cluxury showroom=E2=80=9D on the upper floors where =E2=80=
=9Cunique and exceptional objects=E2=80=9D will be sold for fixed
prices. Sotheby=E2=80=99s has been talking about expanding its luxury retai=
ling capacity since <b>Patrick</b> <b>Drahi</b> acquired the company in 201=
9, but the new showroom in the Paris headquarters is modest in scope=E2=80=
=94about twice the size of the building=E2=80=99s 30-seat caf=C3=A9=E2=80=
=94so the rollout is going slowly. </li><br/><li><i>Sotheby=E2=80=99s annou=
nces leadership of Modern and Contemporary art in Hong Kong</i>: Tomorrow m=
orning, Sotheby=E2=80=99s will release a raft of personnel changes. The pro=
ximal cause is the return of <b>Alex</b> <b>Branczik</b> and <b>Max</b> <b>=
Moore </b>from Hong Kong, who were seconded to the Asian capital of the auc=
tion house for three years to help <b>Nathan Drahi</b>, son of billionaire =
Sotheby=E2=80=99s owner Patrick, kickstart growth. <br/><br/>With a new hea=
dquarters opening in Hong Kong next month, <b>Elaine</b> <b>Holt</b>, who c=
omes from Christie=E2=80=99s, will lead the Modern and Contemporary art tea=
m in Asia, joined by <b>Joseph Yang</b> (formerly of Poly Auction)
and <b>Boris Cornelissen</b> (who had left Sotheby=E2=80=99s to run his own=
 gallery in Australia). Moore has returned to New York, where he will work =
in private sales and run Sotheby=E2=80=99s Sealed, the company=E2=80=99s ex=
periment with blind bidding. Branczik will become the head of Modern and Co=
ntemporary art in Europe. Other new roles will be announced tomorrow. </li>=
</ul></td>
